from faimed3d.all import *

For this tutorial we will use a dataset of mri images for an other study. The study consists out of pelvic TIRM images for the diagnosis of axial spondylarthritis. A typical sign of present active disease is a elevated TIRM signal of the bone marrow next to the sacroiliac joints, which we are aiming to predict with out model.

{% raw %} 
df = pd.read_csv('../../mri-spa/data/train.csv')
df = df[['path_tirm', 'is_valid']].dropna()
df['path_tirm'] = [path.replace('data', '/../mri-spa/mri') for path in df.path_tirm]
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
dls = ImageDataLoaders3D.from_df(df, 
                           #      rescale_method = noop,
                                 item_tfms = ResizeCrop3D(crop_by = (0,0,0), 
                                                         resize_to = (16, 224, 224)))

No rescale method was used. This is not advisable due to high risk of exploding gradients. Falling back to mean scaling.
{% endraw %}

The ImageDataLoaders3D already does some basic rescaling of the input to advoid to large pixel values. As default, all items will be scaled to a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. By using a identity function, as rescale method this behaviour can be turned off, which however is not advisable due to a high risk for exploding gradients during training.

{% raw %} 
xb, yb = dls.one_batch()
show_hist(xb)
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
xb.max_scale().sqrt().show(nrow=16, figsize=(90, 30))
{% endraw %}

The default rescaling method in ImageDataLoaders3D or SegmentationDataLoaders3D is to scale all items to a mean of 0 and a standard deviation (std) of 1.

{% raw %} 
show_hist(xb.mean_scale())
{% endraw %}

However, mean scaling does not change the distribution of pixels, so the histogram is skewed and has a long tail.

{% raw %} 
show_hist(xb.sqrt())
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
show_hist(xb.detach().cpu().hist_scaled())
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
xb.max_scale().sqrt().show(nrow=16, figsize=(90, 30))
{% endraw %}
